Now I can see the bug. Let me look closely at the `AddAutoSpinTimeout` method:

```csharp
private void AddAutoSpinTimeout ()
{
    // Only add timeout if we are initialized and not already spinning
    if (App is { } && (_timeout is { } || !App.Initialized))
    {
        return;
    }

    _timeout = App?.AddTimeout (...);
}
```

The condition on line 205 is wrong. The comment says "Only add timeout if we are initialized and not already spinning", but the code does the opposite - it returns early (doesn't add the timeout) when `App` exists AND (`_timeout` exists OR App is not initialized). 

The logic should be: return early if `App` is null OR `_timeout` already exists OR App is not initialized. But the condition `App is { }` is always true when App exists, and the condition `(!App.Initialized)` makes it return when NOT initialized — but when App is null, it will fall through and call `App?.AddTimeout` which returns null.

Let me also check the `AutoSpin` setter: when `AutoSpin = true` is called in the constructor (line 40), `AddAutoSpinTimeout` is called. At that point, `App` is likely null because the view hasn't been added to a running application yet.

Let me verify my understanding by looking at when `AutoSpin` is set in the scenario

